 "executive_summary": "This study investigated a melanoma-specific TCR (\u03b124\u03b217) engineered via phage display to achieve 30,000-fold enhanced binding affinity (KD = 0.6 nM) to its cognate MHC-I\u2013peptide complex, compared to the low-affinity wild-type TCR (KD range 100 nM\u2013270 \u03bcM). Despite the dramatic increase in overall binding strength mediated primarily through new TCR\u2013MHC contacts, the engineered TCR retained exquisite peptide specificity, remaining sensitive to modifications at every position along the peptide backbone\u2014a hallmark of natural TCR recognition. Thermodynamic analysis revealed that solvation effects play a critical role in maintaining this peptide selectivity, uncoupling the mechanisms of affinity enhancement from those governing sequence discrimination. These findings illuminate how TCRs achieve their characteristic specificity and have implications for rational TCR engineering, particularly for cancer immunotherapy where maintaining peptide discrimination is essential to minimize off-target recognition and autoimmunity risk.",
